							"uid" : {
								"__type" : "uid",
								"uidString" : "9eGHS0ZBTHu1XCbmyhK/wA=="
							},
							"paragraphStyle" : {
								"__type" : "textStyle"
							},
							"string" : "A basic chat has no notion of the expected output. With services that support structured output, we can define the expected response schema. For example, in the previous chat, we received a plain string, so it is shown as plain text even if it contains Markdown notation. If we specify that we expect Markdown, we can do so through {{gtMethod:GtLChat>>#markdownResponse}}:"
						},
						{
							"__type" : "textSnippet",
							"children" : {
								"__type" : "snippets",
								"items" : [ ]
							},
							"createEmail" : {
								"__type" : "email",
								"emailString" : "<unknown>"
							},
							"createTime" : {
								"__type" : "time",
								"time" : {
									"__type" : "dateAndTime",
									"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-03-04T22:41:48.693731+01:00"
								}
							},
							"editEmail" : {
								"__type" : "email",
								"emailString" : "<unknown>"
							},
							"editTime" : {
								"__type" : "time",
								"time" : {
									"__type" : "dateAndTime",
									"dateAndTimeString" : "2026-03-13T22:32:17.24762+01:00"
								}
							},
							"uid" : {
								"__type" : "uid",
								"uidString" : "d3aR59JpTzSlF0+6ewLVXg=="
							},
							"paragraphStyle" : {
								"__type" : "textStyle"
							},
							"string" : "Executing this chat now shows a Markdown-specific view in addition to the plain text view. This works as follows: the engine sends the expected response schema in the request, and when the response arrives, it transparently instantiates objects that conform to the specified schema. In our case, the object is an instance of {{gtClass:GtLMarkdown}}, and that object knows how to present itself through a styled editor."
						}
					]
				},
